The United Kingdom has announced the banning of civilian Russian aircraft from its airspace. “No aircraft on a scheduled service which is owned, chartered or operated by a person connected with Russia, or which is registered in Russia shall fly in United Kingdom airspace,” reads a bulletin to pilots just published by the UK Department For Transport. Russian airline Aeroflot currently operates direct flights between Moscow and London-Heathrow and Gatwick, according to its website. Russia/Ukraine Faceoff: UK Government Announces Visa Concessions… Boris Johnson Orders Asset Freeze For All Russian Banks The bulletin also bans Russian aircraft from the airspace above the United Kingdom’s territorial sea. The restriction goes into effect at 7 p.m. EST and is set to expire on May 23.